Date: Wed 9 Oct 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Star Online, Wed 9 Oct 2002 [edited]
<http://www.thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2002/10/9/nation/tpideng&sec=nation>

Malaysia (Perak): Alarming Rise in Dengue Cases
-----------------------------------------------
The increased incidence of dengue fever in Perak in the first 9 months this
year is alarming, said state Health, Environment, Science and Technology
Committee chairman Datuk Ho Cheng Wang yesterday. He urged residents not to
be unduly worried although there was a 82 percent increase this year as
compared to the same period last year. He said during the first 9 months of
this year, 1659 cases, including 6 deaths, were recorded in Perak compared
to only 913 cases, including 2 deaths, during the same period last year.
"There is an increase of 746 cases or 82 percent this year," he said.
Ho said the Health Department and the respective local authorities were
monitoring the situation and taking immediate remedial actions, including
fogging activities. "Please co-operate with the authorities and residents
can play their part by ensuring that their compounds are kept clean," he
told a press conference here yesterday. Ho attributed the ongoing rainy
season as one of the main causes for the incidence of dengue fever.
He said this year's fatalities occurred in areas under the jurisdiction of
the Ipoh City Council (2 deaths) and a death each in the districts of Kuala
Kangsar, Kinta, Batang Padang, Larut, Matang and Selama. He also allayed
fears of residents in Kampar that there was a major outbreak of dengue
fever there. "Based on statistics recorded between 22 and 28 Sep 2002,
there were only 28 cases there and between 29 Sep and 6 Oct 2002 18 cases,
including one death," he said. Ho said there were enough hospital beds for
dengue fever victims at the Kampar hospital and that any shortfall could be
covered by Tapah hospital.
