[3]
Date: Sat 12 Oct 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Star Online, Sat 12 Oct 2002 [edited]
<http://www.thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2002/10/12/nation/klgdengu&sec=nation>

Malaysia: Selangor Placed on Dengue Alert
-----------------------------------------
Selangor has been placed on dengue alert following 3 deaths reported
between 29 Sep and 5 Oct 2002, raising the total fatalities so far to 10
this year. State Health Committee chairman Datuk Tang See Hang said
Selayang has the highest number of fatal cases with 4, followed by Subang
Jaya and Klang (2 each) and Kuala Langat and Shah Alam (one each). He said
there was a 30 percent rise in dengue cases in the state compared to last
year, with a total of 5986 cases already reported. Selayang Municipal
Council topped the list with 1367 cases followed by Subang Jaya Municipal
Council with 1165 cases.
Tang said the state government, health officials, and local authorities
would meet on Thu 24 Oct 2002 to find solutions to control the rise in
dengue cases and deaths related to it. "The state government views the
situation (3 deaths in a week) as critical considering that there had been
only 7 deaths up to 29 Sep this year. The present situation is also bad as
there were only 3 deaths for the whole of last year," he said. He added
that: "The statistics showed that the dengue outbreak is prone in urban
areas in the state. This could be attributed to the massive ongoing
development resulting in stagnant water being collected at construction
sites. The current rainy weather condition have also made it difficult for
the authorities to contain the outbreak." Tang urged the public to view the
outbreak seriously and take preventive measures by keeping their premises
and surroundings clear from potential water traps such as unwanted
containers, flower pots, and tires.
In Ipoh, Perak Health Department director Dr Abdul Razak Kechik urged those
suffering from dengue fever to be isolated and placed under a mosquito net
to avoid infecting others. He added that: "The _Aedes_ mosquito only
becomes a vector (carrier) of dengue virus once it bites and sucks blood of
a human being suffering from dengue fever. Dengue virus will then multiply
in the body of the _Aedes_ mosquito, which will spread the fever to other
people. Animals cannot carry [transmit] dengue virus. Other mosquitoes like
_Culex_ might bite someone with dengue fever, but the virus will die inside
the insect. Similarly, not all _Aedes_ mosquitoes might be carrying dengue
virus, especially when they have just emerged from the larval
stage. People with dengue fever must report to the authorities."
[Byline: Elan Perumal]
