Source: Express India, Wed 9 Oct 2002 [edited]
<http://cities.expressindia.com/fullstory.php?newsid=31825>

India (Maharashtra & Gujarat): 36 Dengue Cases Reported in Pune
------------------------------------------------
As of Mon 7 Oct 2002, the National Institute of Virology (NIV) has sent 2
teams of entomologists to scout areas in the city and surrounding villages
for infected mosquitoes. So far 20 samples from outside Pune and 2 cases at
Sassoon General Hospital have tested positive for dengue virus by the NIV.
As of Mon 7 Oct 2002, the KEM Hospital dengue [unit], which is testing
samples of suspected dengue virus free of cost, had detected 9 more cases
from Dhankawadi, Pimpri, Kolhapur, Bhor, Wadgaon, and Wagholi. "So far
there are a total of 36 patients in the city undergoing treatment for
dengue" said Dr Rajesh Gadia, Chief of the Dengue [Unit] at KEM hospital.
Senior scientists at the NIV did not rule out an outbreak of dengue fever
[also] at Surat in Gujarat and said that they had confirmed 11 dengue cases
at Shirur, 4 at Satara, 3 at Nanded , and 2 at Solapur. According to the
scientists, over 50 samples have tested positive for dengue virus at Surat.
NIV scientists said that they had not received many samples of suspected
dengue cases from the city barring 2 from Sassoon Hospital. They have
started collecting infected mosquitoes from various parts specially Shirur.
NIV scientists however admitted that there has been an increase in the
number of cases of dengue since 1998. From the outbreak in Hadapsar in
1998, there has been an increase this year in the number of cases that are
being sporadically reported from various parts. Urbanisation and increased
transport facilities is also one of the many factors for the rise in the
number of patients infected with dengue virus. When contacted, Dr Anil
Ravetkar, Chief Medical Officer, Pune Municipal Corporation (PMC) said that
there had been no further increase in the number of dengue cases.
